YES or NO on Polymarket?

Sunny Shi

Aug 12, 2024 ⋅  14 min read

Key Insights

  • Polymarket is a prediction market on Polygon that has experienced remarkable organic growth and attention this year.
  • While current volumes are largely election driven, non-election volumes have also been growing at a rapid rate.
  • We explore several of Polymarket’s potential growth drivers, including sizable funding, a potential TGE, and the continued financialization of prediction.
  • There are risks to the thesis as well, which include a recent uptick in competition, the need for market making incentives, and a lack of recurring markets.
  • Although we foresee a drop in metrics immediately following the election cycle, there is a strong case for Polymarket’s sustainability.

Polymarket’s Success Story

The recent surge in Polymarket's activity, driven by the 2024 US presidential election, has brought new levels of mainstream attention to crypto prediction markets.

The platform has grown rapidly year-to-date. As of the end of July, open interest is up over 9x to ~$87 million and monthly volumes are up over 6x to ~$387 million.

Polymarket’s user acquisition is particularly noteworthy considering the vast majority of crypto applications are lacking users. The platform is rapidly growing its sign-ups, adding more than 100 thousand new accounts in the last two months. We believe Polymarket is on the verge of finding product-market fit, and is undoubtedly one of the breakthrough apps of the year.

Polymarket’s growth story and impact go further than the circular speculation typically found in crypto. As a prediction market, it leverages the “wisdom of the crowd” to give insights into major outcomes across politics, business, and markets. It can also price real-time events remarkably fast, which makes it a powerful tool for live news.

There is a clear demand for these insights. Polymarket’s Google search interest and web traffic have surpassed those of Uniswap, and its election odds have been cited by the likes of the Wall Street Journal, CNN, and Donald Trump.

Further, a new use case for prediction markets is being tested. Prediction market pricing is being explored as a way to settle DAO proposal votes through a concept called “futarchy” with MetaDAO spearheading this initiative.

All of this interest in Polymarket’s predictions leads to more organic attention and marketing for the platform, which has only increased the protocol’s relevance.

However, a few key questions remain. Can Polymarket sustain growth post-election and will it survive an onslaught of new competitors? In this report, we’ll address those concerns by taking a look at Polymarket’s mechanics, breaking down its growth prospects, and assessing its key risks.

Polymarket’s Design

Main Components

Polymarket is a prediction market founded in 2020 on Polygon.

The platform allows traders to speculate on event markets that are resolved by an oracle. Traders transact with conditional tokens built using Gnosis’ conditional tokens framework (CTF) which represent tradable YES or NO outcomes to events. Tokens can be bought or sold anytime through an order book. Key components include:

  • Markets for users to speculate on the outcome of various real-world events, from politics and finance to entertainment and sports. Markets allow participants to take positions on whether a particular result will or will not happen, and are resolved by an oracle. A specific Polymarket “market” focuses on one topic or event. Although users can submit new market creation proposals through Polymarket’s discord, Polymarket has discretion over which markets get created due to the intricacies involved with wording their resolutions.
  • Traders (speculators or hedgers) who bet on the likelihood of potential outcomes if they believe the true odds of a certain event are higher than currently implied odds. If a Polymarket trader believes that the true odds of Biden resigning from office is 30%, and current prices imply only a 15% probability, they may consider it a worthwhile bet (even if they think the outcome is unlikely). Prediction markets are zero sum in nature, with speculators taking opposing stances against one another. If Biden does indeed resign from office, speculators who bet on the alternative option would see their shares rendered worthless.
  • Liquidity providers who market make for specific markets. For example, market makers may choose to only provide liquidity in higher volume markets. Like on any other DEX, market makers profit by operating a spread and by earning fees. Unlike sportsbooks, prediction markets allow for the liquid trading of shares even when a market is unresolved. Speculators can sell their shares anytime for a profit or a loss as prices change, which means market makers play an important role. Polymarket employs a hybrid-decentralized central limit order book (CLOB) similar to dYdX v3 where operators provide offchain matching and ordering while settlement and execution occur onchain.
  • Oracles who provide resolutions to betting markets. These oracles require human input given the complexity involved with settling a prediction market. Polymarket has integrated with the UMA optimistic oracle, which allows anyone to submit a resolution. Resolutions are held as true if unchallenged for a length of time. In rare cases when disputes arise, they are settled by UMA’s tokenholders.
  • Outcome or Conditional Tokens that enable the trading experience. Positions on Polymarket are referred to as “outcome tokens” or “conditional tokens”, and represent binary outcomes (either “YES” or “NO”). Within the same market pool, tokens trade against each other to determine pricing while maintaining a ratio that adds up to $1. For example, in a simple two-option YES or NO pool, the prices of one pair of YES and NO outcome tokens will always add up to $1. When the market is settled, those who own one share of the winning outcome are paid $1, while those who own one share of the losing outcome receive nothing. This leads to a simple and intuitive user experience where speculators can both deduce the payout for outcome shares and associate the implied probability just by looking at the price. Buying a share worth $0.75 means the market is pricing 75% odds for that outcome, and your profit per share would be $0.25 ($1 - $0.75). For its outcome tokens, Polymarket uses the conditional tokens framework (CTF) developed by the Gnosis protocol that builds on top of the ERC1155 token standard.

Token and Incentives

Polymarket has neither a token nor an ongoing points program, which makes the volume and user growth on the platform even more impressive. No announcement has been made about any potential TGE.

With that being said, Polymarket has paid out over $3 million dollars YTD in USDC incentives through its liquidity rewards program. These rewards have gone towards incentivizing market making activity in order to improve overall liquidity depth on the platform. The most popular markets can pay up to 600 USDC in daily rewards to liquidity providers.

What Happens Now?

While Polymarket’s growth has been impressive, there are concerns around whether it can sustain it beyond the U.S. election cycles.

Election Volumes

These concerns seem legitimate when observing Polymarket’s current volume drivers. As of July 30th, 2024, 17 election-driven markets account for ~94% of the total notional volume of the 32 most active markets. One might question what happens to these volumes after the election ends.

In response, some encouraging trends are worth highlighting:

  • Polymarket’s non-election volumes have grown at an average rate of ~113% month-over-month since the start of the year.
  • Polymarket has consistently improved its product, UX, and marketing. This may be seen from the fact that compared to the previous election cycle, notional volumes are up over 50x on the main election market already.
  • Polymarket has also found success in sports, global politics, and finance. Among its top 20 markets, there are markets on Olympic medals (~$8.5 million notional volume), the Venezuelan Presidential Election (~$6 million notional volume), and Fed Fund Rates (~$10 million notional volume).

Finally, another perspective is that the election may act as an onboarding tool for Polymarket. By assuming a 25% MoM growth rate for non-election volumes - we estimate that Polymarket can still do ~$380 million in non-election monthly volumes by the end of the year, which annualizes to ~$4.5 billion. This would be higher than some traditional DEXs like SushiSwap or Trader Joe.

Net net, while there may be an immediate drawdown in activity following the end of the election, we expect Polymarket volumes to still remain markedly higher on an annual basis.

What is the Future for Polymarket?

Growth Thesis

Product Innovation

Prediction markets have yet to significantly innovate beyond their original designs. Polymarket can continue to iterate on its product, and offer more features to both traders and data-seekers. Some potential actions include:

  • Experimenting with leverage.
  • Offering more “degen” market types, such as parlays.
  • Allowing the prediction market to be used for futarchy, which can dictate DAO governance proposals.

As the largest distributor of conditional tokens, Polymarket will stand to benefit from enhancements in prediction market utility.

New Integrations

Polymarket has recently integrated with Farcaster Frames, increasing its overall accessibility and improving its mobile UX. Future integrations can continue to widen Polymarket’s audience and usability.

Funding

In May, Polymarket announced that they had received new backing from notable names such as Vitalik Buterin and Founders Fund. More importantly, the protocol has access to a war chest of $70 million, which it can spend on marketing, growth, and development. This money also allows Polymarket to make key hires, evidenced by the recent pickup of renowned statistician, pollster, and journalist Nate Silver to help bolster the politics offering.

Token Generation Event (TGE)

If Polymarket decides to announce a TGE, the protocol can transition to incentivizing users through tokens and/or a preceding points program instead of paying out USDC.

Financialization of Prediction

A long-tail growth vector could be that Polymarket’s outcome tokens become a financial instrument for hedging. Predictions offer pure-pay exposure to specific geopolitical outcomes, which can become immensely valuable for investors who have limited options at the moment.

Take one of Polymarket’s currently active markets - Will China Invade Taiwan in 2024?

As of the writing the market is pricing in a 9% chance that China does invade Taiwan in 2024. The payout would be ~1000% for current speculators who buy YES shares. If you are an investor with positions in any stocks that are dependent on the semiconductor supply chain, it may be worthwhile to hedge that exposure through Polymarket so that you are covered in the scenario that China invades Taiwan and severely disrupts TSMC production.

It should be noted that U.S. based institutions don’t have access to Polymarket as it is unapproved by the CFTC, and so this would only apply to individual investors or global managers. That is still a large addressable market, and if Polymarket can strengthen liquidity across the platform, the inclusion of prediction shares into portfolios becomes a real possibility.

Risks to the Thesis

Growing Competition

Owing to Polymarket’s success, a race has begun to build the next big prediction market that can challenge it. Announcements for new prediction markets have come from Vega Network, Drift on Solana, Predict.fun on Blast, and developers on TON and MegaETH.

We expect this to be a broad trend, and soon upstart prediction markets will be up and running on every chain.

Mitigating this risk is the fact that Polymarket has already built out its brand awareness to a mass audience.

Polymarket has the most X followers out of active prediction markets. The word-of-mouth attention it has attracted presents a powerful advantage, as Polymarket is already top-of-mind for most potential speculators.

Polymarket should also see benefits from being the first mover to reach scale. First movers often do quite well in crypto, evidenced by winners like Bitcoin, Ethereum and Uniswap. However, Polymarket should avoid complacency unless it wants to risk ending up like Opensea, who was outcompeted by its younger rival Blur.

Retaining Market Makers

As mentioned earlier, Polymarket pays out USDC incentives to liquidity providers. The reason Polymarket has opted to prioritize rewards for market makers over traders is the fact that the market making experience on a prediction market is uniquely challenging:

  • Prediction market makers are subjected to a higher amount of toxic flow as critical information for settling these markets may come from anywhere (a tweet, live stream, TV interview, etc.). While toxic flow can occur in any market, prediction markets have wide coverage in obscure topics, fewer sources of data, low regulatory oversight, and thinner volume.
  • This is worsened by random, instantaneous, and sharp volatility. For example, the “Will Biden Finish his Term?” market can be immediately settled if Biden drops a tweet announcing his resignation from the presidency. This will instantly cause shares to reprice towards $1 or $0, even before shares are officially resolved by the oracle, putting passive market makers at a disadvantage. For sophisticated market makers, there are no proven algorithms and no other sources to hedge your book as Polymarket is your largest supplier of prediction outcome shares.

To compensate for all of the above, makers will set wider spreads, which is why Polymarket gives out higher rewards to liquidity providers who provide bids within a tighter spread. We believe most market makers on Polymarket would not be on the platform were it not for the daily rewards. Thus, we view incentivizing market makers as a necessity for growth. Can Polymarket do this indefinitely?

Obviously not, but to mitigate this, Polymarket’s CEO has hinted at the potential to turn on fees down the line. We believe that if Polymarket can establish its leadership position, it can be rather aggressive on fees. To compare, sportsbook users are accustomed to over 4% in average fees on every line, and given how difficult it is to facilitate liquid prediction markets, Polymarket can justify the fee premium over a traditional DEX. A portion of these fees can sustain an ongoing liquidity rewards program that can retain market makers on Polymarket.

Furthermore, this is a risk to all other prediction markets, not just Polymarket. As the largest incumbent, Polymarket is better suited to continue to incentivize liquidity from its larger “balance sheet” and potential token (which may trade at a higher valuation compared to upstart competitors).

Ecosystem Risk

Polymarket is live only on Polygon and as such is somewhat tied to the success of Polygon and its ecosystem. While Polygon continues to do well, Solana is currently the flavor of the month among users and traders. These users may find it easier to use prediction markets on Solana instead of bridging over to Polygon.

To mitigate this, Polymarket can eventually move to deploying on multiple EVM chains, but may risk fracturing liquidity and worsening UX in the process.

Failure to Generate Recurring Activity

Another problem, as highlighted by Kyle Samani, is whether prediction markets can generate recurring lifetime value. Prediction markets have long-tail events with uncertain resolution timelines that can extend to over a year (such as the “will ____ happen in 2024” markets). Crypto users may prefer the instant gratification and constant stimulation of trading memecoins instead. Can prediction markets stimulate enough recurring “evergreen” volume from users over long periods of time?

To mitigate this, Polymarket can offer shorter timeframe markets, like ones that end in a month, a week, or even a few days. We don’t think Polymarket needs to stray from its core competency in politics and pivot to markets like sports, where competition is much more intense. Instead, the protocol can lean into its strengths. Potential cabinet appointees, House and Senate races, and whether the sitting President starts a war are all examples of potential follow-on markets. Polymarket can generate relevant political betting topics on a recurring basis and market them to their now substantial audience.

Conclusion

After becoming one of crypto’s hottest sensations, Polymarket’s biggest challenge now is to retain election volume and drive future growth amidst higher competition. While we see Polymarket giving up a large chunk of its current volume from the election cycle, in the coming years, it can leverage its leadership position and growing adoption to expand its influence.
